    "what-is-crc": "What is CRC?",
    "what-is-crc-description-markdown": "CRC (Cyclic Redundancy Check) is a type of checksum algorithm used to detect errors in digital data and storage devices. It produces a fixed-size checksum value, commonly ranging from 8 to 64 bits, that serves as a digital fingerprint of the data.\n\n**Key characteristics:**\n- **Error detection**: Designed specifically to catch common types of errors in data transmission and storage\n- **Deterministic**: The same input always produces the same CRC value\n- **Fast computation**: Efficient to calculate using polynomial division algorithms\n- **Cyclic property**: Based on polynomial arithmetic in finite fields\n- **Collision detection**: Different data will typically produce different CRC values\n\n**Common CRC variants:**\n- **CRC-8**: 8-bit checksum, used in small embedded systems\n- **CRC-16**: 16-bit checksum, used in MODBUS and USB protocols\n- **CRC-32**: 32-bit checksum, widely used in Ethernet, ZIP files, and PNG images\n- **CRC-64**: 64-bit checksum, used for larger data sets requiring higher reliability\n\n**Common uses:**\n- Network protocols (Ethernet frames, TCP checksums)\n- File formats (ZIP, PNG, MPEG)\n- Storage systems (hard drives, SSDs)\n- Data transmission verification\n- Embedded systems and IoT devices"
